**Summary:** Generative AI interfaces with prompt-based inputs are challenging to use because they require users to articulate their intent in words, which is challenging. Hybrid user interfaces that combine prompt-based inputs with graphical user inputs (GUI) have the potential to make AI image generation tools more usable by reducing users’ cognitive load and improving discoverability.

---

The majority of tools that are used for AI image generation have **prompt-based user inputs**. Users write a text prompt and the AI model then responds by creating images that match the prompt.&nbsp;

When an interface relies solely on text prompts as user inputs, it is **challenging for inexperienced or [low-articulation users](https://jakobnielsenphd.substack.com/p/prompt-driven-ai-ux-hurts-usability)**&nbsp; to achieve their goals. Users may often write prompts that they feel represent their intent but receive images that miss the mark entirely. Additionally, it is cognitively taxing for users to articulate every action they want to perform as prose.&nbsp;

### **Method**

I studied how users create images through Midjourney, one of the most popular image-generation tools. Studying Midjourney was uniquely interesting because it offers its services through a [Discord server](https://docs.midjourney.com/docs/midjourney-discord), where any member can see what prompts other users are writing and what images they’re creating. This data captures real-world usage and has high ecological validity. I analyzed over 100 prompts and the resultant images, and traced the iterations users went through to generate their final images.&nbsp;

I also looked at eight different prompt-writing guides for AI image-generation tools compiled by expert users. These guides describe how to construct prompts to get the best images. This helped me understand the gap between how beginners and experts approached writing prompts.&nbsp;

## **The Articulation Barrier in Image Generation**

In **“**[Prompt-Driven AI UX Hurts Usability](https://jakobnielsenphd.substack.com/p/prompt-driven-ai-ux-hurts-usability)**”**,&nbsp; Jakob Nielsen discusses why it is challenging to articulate your needs in writing. This challenge creates a barrier between the user and the computer, especially when writing prompts.&nbsp;

Definition: The **articulation barrier** is the persistent difficulty faced by users when trying to verbalize their intent into a prompt.&nbsp;

The articulation barrier is even higher for image prompts as compared to text prompts, like those for ChatGPT. Image prompts are far more complex and must capture abstract concepts like different visual aesthetics. Several prompts on Midjourney contained terms that were well outside the bounds of basic English. These terms are crucial for influencing the visual properties of the generated images.&nbsp;

For example, a user trying to generate an image of a futuristic city by simply using the prompt, “futuristic city”. Adding a style word, like “cyberpunk”, can produce a very different image -- in this case,&nbsp; a more detailed and vividly colored result.&nbsp;

Prompt: “Futuristic city” (left) vs. Prompt: “Futuristic city, cyberpunk” (right) generated by Stable Diffusion

I frequently observed the use of similar terms like *synth-wave*, *steampunk*, *octane render*, *dystopian*, *unreal engine,* *psychedelic*, *art nouveau*, etc. These terms are **rooted in specific cultural and creative trends** known only to a few who are exposed to them.&nbsp; Thus, if users are unfamiliar with certain cultural and creative trends, they lack the associated terminology, thus preventing them from recreating those aesthetics.&nbsp;

\
Another common technique I observed was **naming certain visual artists** whose style users wanted to capture in their generated images, like *Hokusai*, *Diego Rivera*, *Monet*, and *Miyazaki*. This technique of appending artists' names to prompts helps recreate specific visual properties much more easily than trying to define the brushwork, style, or color palette of generated artwork. “Swirling brushstrokes with bright, solid colors, and abstract, post-impressionistic imagery” is much harder for a user to articulate than “Van Gogh’s style” (assuming the user knows who Van Gogh is). While this technique itself serves to reduce the articulation barrier somewhat, it requires comprehensive knowledge of different artists and what their styles look like.

Users often chain together numerous terms rooted in cultural and creative trends as well as names of artists in their prompts to create images with the exact visual properties they are looking for (see the image and prompt below).&nbsp;

\
However, being able to use this technique demands a level of cultural exposure that not everyone possesses. This shuts the door for many to explore creating a wide variety of aesthetics when generating images. **Users may be able to visualize images in their minds but often lack the vocabulary to write the required prompt.** This is similar to the problem solved by ‘[Keyword Foraging](https://www.nngroup.com/articles/keyword-foraging/)’ during search. However, foraging is not possible here as there’s no way (yet) to find the right keywords just by using the image generation tool, which offers no clues.&nbsp;

\
Prompt-writing guides emphasize the importance of being specific with language. They encourage prompters to use many adjectives and rich descriptions of scenes to create images that better match the prompt.&nbsp;

Articulating the image a user wants to create with enough descriptors is cognitively taxing. **Users must pay special attention to writing in all elements of the image they hold in their minds** (many of which they may not even know the terms for)**.** This effort compounds quickly when users have to repeat the articulation process many times. Rarely did I observe a user in Midjourney stop after generating one image. Most users attempted to generate an image multiple times by iterating on the prompt. They changed, added, or removed words, or rephrased the entire prompt. They repeated the process until they reached images they were happy with (or gave up).

## **Solution Exploration: Hybrid Interfaces**

&nbsp;The articulation barrier is a usability challenge for AI image-generation tools.&nbsp; The problem statements, or [how-might-we statements](https://www.nngroup.com/articles/problem-statements/), in this scenario, are:

- How might we enable users to generate images with different visual properties without requiring them to know advanced vocabulary, complex terms, and cultural references?
- How might we make it easier for users to be more descriptive in their prompts.

Prompting gives the user flexibility to create images that they envision in their minds. Retaining this flexibility is important to preserve the value of generative AI. Thus having a textbox for the prompt input was required.&nbsp;

At the same time, having solutions where users don’t need to know advanced terms from memory or find it easier to articulate more descriptively, led me to explore graphical user interfaces (GUI) which present options for users to click on and select from.&nbsp;

### **Presenting Visual Properties as Options to Select From**

Since advanced vocabulary, complex terms, and cultural references are outside many users’ knowledge, I explored the concept of presenting different visual properties as options to select from. I considered showing thumbnail images with the visual effect each term would have on the generated image. Users could choose and apply that effect without needing to know the name of the term and make their decision based on the visual clue provided in the thumbnail. For instance, to create an aesthetic that has pain splashes and bright colors, users can visually recognize the Jackson Pollock thumbnail as the appropriate effect and select it, rather than needing to know about Jackson Pollock’s style and use it as a verbal reference.&nbsp;

