**Patterns in writing image prompts**

\

**Research:**&nbsp;

\

- Analysing Midjourney prompts on the discord server - value of **naturally occurring data**, high ecological validity. Mention why this is good for this context and how other sources might be useful for other contexts.&nbsp;
- Prompt engineering guides and tutorials - hit on things that point to usability problems, common themes. User data in a way.&nbsp;

\

**Findings:**

\

- Users have to repeatedly iterate on their prompts to arrive at images they are happy with. They do so by changing the wording of their prompts and adding/removing terms. Prompt writing guides often emphasise the importance of being descriptive and specific.&nbsp;
  - Examples: Show the progression of images along with iterations of the prompts

\

- Users often need to use advanced vocabulary to render desired aesthetic properties in images. For example, if someone wants to generate futuristic looking city scapes, they might use terms like “cyberpunk” “octane render” “synthwave” or “dystopian”.&nbsp;
  - Example prompt - *“galactic drive, in the style of cyberpunk realism, magali villeneuve, nightcore, city portraits, outrun, subtle emotions, amandine van ray --ar 16:9”*
    - This is not literacy, it’s a different kind of literacy. Visual literacy, **cultural literacy?**&nbsp;&nbsp;
    - Traditional literacy + cultural literacy -> double problem
    - Venn diagram
    - Two examples of images with an without descriptive terms

